node.text:
The past year has been a stressful one! We probably aren’t the only ones noticing that extra stress, our kids are too. 

It's an excellent time to remind ourselves of positive emotional regulation strategies. 

Some of those strategies can be: 

✔️ Using a sensory bin, bottle or bag ✔️ Taking a break to go get a drink
✔️ Deep breathing techniques 
✔️ Taking a walk 
✔️ Heavy work (proprioception) activities 
✔️ Coloring or drawing 
✔️ Reading 

Addressing emotions and providing emotional regulation tools will be so important in the coming year as we all hopefully get back to a “normal” school year. 

That is why I have teamed up with some other authors, therapists, and educators and created an incredible resource just for YOU!

The Creating Connections Toolkit includes high-quality, “quick win” resources that will give you what you need right now to help your child or student learn to recognize and manage their emotions.

This is the second year (and my first!!) of the sale, so if you purchased last year, this year’s products are completely BRAND NEW! There are no duplicates of any of the products from last year. 

This digital download toolkit includes resources to help with emotional regulation, sensory processing, and mindfulness and affirmations for all ages. 

Addressing each of these areas can help build stronger connections between you and your students. 

For 5 days, we’ve massively discounted the Creating Connections Toolkit by 93%. That means between now and Tuesday, July 13, you can get $270 worth of products for just $19!

node.text:
Creating an obstacle course is much easier than you think. I grabbed a few outdoor toys like our toddler slide and basketball hoop and sidewalk chalk; and other supplies like pit balls, a cardboard box and painter’s tape. Have multiple ages kids? Get your older kids to help create one for their younger sibling! This was a total hit with everyone! To help you create your own, I created a post with 20 more fun and easy to create backyard obstacle courses for kids.  From a spy training course to a pool noodle course to a water park course. See the full list using the link in my profile. 
AGE: 2 years + 
MESS Level: low 
DIFFICULTY TO CREATE: low
SKILLS DEVELOPED:  gross motor skills, hand-eye coordination, imaginative play, creativity.

node.text:
I partnered with @michaelsstores #ad #makeitwithmichaels to create these 3 fun sensory bottle crafts!

HOW TO MAKE

1. Take your sensory bottle and add animals and glitter.

2. Fill 2/3 of the sensory bottle with warm water.

3. Fill the rest of the sensory bottle with clear glue.

4. Close tightly and shake. You will get some bubbles. These will go away shortly.

5. Decorate the outside of the sensory bottle with the stickers.

6. Seal the sensory bottle with duct tape.

7. Shake and enjoy!

WHAT YOU'LL NEED TO MAKE THE DINOSAUR SENSORY BOTTLE

- Warm water

- Sensory bottle

https://www.michaels.com/sensory-bottle-by-artminds/10551888.html

- Green glitter

https://www.michaels.com/extra-fine-glitter-stacker-artminds/10226109.html

-Dinosaur stickers

So I am jumping on the obstacle course bandwagon here and we decided to take ours into the backyard! Creating an obstacle course is much easier than I thought. I grabbed a few outdoor toys like our toddler slide and basketball hoop and sidewalk chalk; and other supplies like pit balls, a cardboard box and painter’s tape. This was a total hit with everyone! To help you create your own, I created a post with 20 more fun and easy to create backyard obstacle courses for kids.  From a spy training course to a pool noodle course to a water park course. See the full list using the link in my profile.

node.text:
FRISBEE SKATING 
Here is an easy outdoor gross motor activity for preschoolers. Grab two frisbees and use them as skates⛸! They can either do it bare foot, so their feet stick to the frisbee or with shoes. This works best on slightly wet grass. So grab your hose and give your grass a quick spray beforehand. Then hand your little one two frisbees and challenge them to skate across the grass. You can easily turn this into a mini outdoor skating dance party! Turn on some tunes 🎶 and let them get creative with some dance moves!
AGE: 3 years old + 
MESS Level: low
DIFFICULTY TO CREATE: low
SKILLS DEVELOPED:  gross motor skills, imaginative play, creativity.

🍨HOMEMADE ICE CREAM🍨 
{Find the full recipe instructions using the link in my bio}
Looking for a fun and easy snack-tivity for tomorrow. Check your fridge and cupboards for these simple ingredients to made your very own batch of delicious vanilla ice cream! Yes, you heard that correctly: make your own ICE CREAM🍨🍨🍨🍨! This activity has everything (see the skills developed section below). Let them mix the ingredients; run around the house (or outside!) shaking it; the serve and enjoy!
HERE’S WHAT YOU’LL NEED:
🍦Large Ziplock bag
🍦Small Ziplock bag
🍦1 cup of Half and Half
🍦1/2 teaspoon of pure vanilla extract
🍦2 tablespoons of granulated sugar
🍦1/3 cup of Kosher salt
🍦3 cups of ice
🍦Toppings like chocolate sauce and sprinkles
AGE: 2 years old +

Check out this list of 25 fun activities to enjoy to ensure that your little one has  plenty of fresh memories when they start school! These are a great way to cap your summer!
A few ideas to try;
1. Go fruit picking for late season fruit;
2. Make giant bubbles; 
3. Go fishing 🎣 ; or 
4. Go camping in your backyard!
See the full list of things to do before summer ☀️ ends and school 🏫🎒begins using the link in my bio. 

AGE: 2 years old + 
MESS Level: low
DIFFICULTY TO CREATE: low
SKILLS DEVELOPED:  fine and gross motor skills, hand-eye coordination, memory, imaginative play, creativity.
__________
PLaY🌈CReaTivEly
#happytoddlerplaytime

💦POOL NOODLE WATER WALL💦 
Looking for a fun and easy water activity for tomorrow? Pull out a few pool noodles and funnels to create this super easy water wall! Add some jugs, measuring cups and bowls to capture the water 💦! A great one to entertain and even educate! This easy STEM activity to talk about gravity and water conservation (why we capture and reuse the water). Head over to the blog for more summer activity ideas!

AGE: 2 years old + 
MESS Level: low 
DIFFICULTY TO CREATE: low
SKILLS DEVELOPED:  gross motor skills, hand-eye coordination, imaginative play, creativity.
__________
PLaY🌈CReaTivEly
